INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '55c55b11-2fc4-4d19-abed-f0a58afedf3f',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Terraform + Ansible — Bridging Provisioning and Configuration with null_resource$escape$,
  $escape$Terraform provisions infrastructure; Ansible configures it. The standard bridge is a `null_resource` with a `local-exec` provisioner that fires an `ansible-playbook` command after `aws_instance` (or `azurerm_linux_virtual_machine`) creation. Pass the public IP directly from the resource output into the inventory argument — no static inventory files needed.

Ansible's idempotency model mirrors Terraform's: each module (`apt`, `service`, `template`) checks current state before acting. Re-running a playbook produces the same result, just like `terraform apply` on a converged stack is a no-op. This makes the pair safe to run in CI on every deploy.

The catch: Terraform provisioners only execute on resource creation, not every `apply`. To force re-execution when a playbook changes, key your `triggers` map on `filemd5("playbooks/web.yml")`. This gives you Terraform-native drift detection for configuration, not just infrastructure.

Never embed secrets in the `command` string — use `ANSIBLE_VAULT_PASSWORD_FILE` or pull values from `aws_ssm_parameter` data sources and export them as environment variables in the provisioner block.$escape$,
  $escape$resource "aws_instance" "web" {
  ami           = data.aws_ami.ubuntu.id
  instance_type = "t3.micro"
  key_name      = aws_key_pair.deployer.key_name
}

resource "null_resource" "configure" {
  triggers = {
    instance_id  = aws_instance.web.id
    playbook_hash = filemd5("${path.module}/playbooks/web.yml")
  }

  provisioner "local-exec" {
    command = <<-EOT
      ansible-playbook -i '${aws_instance.web.public_ip},' \
        --private-key ${var.ssh_key_path} \
        --ssh-extra-args='-o StrictHostKeyChecking=no' \
        ${path.module}/playbooks/web.yml
    EOT
  }
}$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
